# SBK Cursor AI Rules

> This file contains Cursor-specific rules for the SBK repository. Cursor AI reads this file to understand project conventions.

## Project Overview

SBK (Storage Benchmark Kit) is a Java framework for benchmarking storage systems. It uses Gradle for building, requires JDK 25, and has ~55 storage drivers.

## Key Conventions

### Build System
- Use `./gradlew check` to verify changes
- Use `./gradlew installDist` to build distribution
- JDK 25 is REQUIRED (set SBK_JAVA_HOME or JAVA_HOME)
- New drivers must be added to BOTH `settings-drivers.gradle` and `build-drivers.gradle`

### Code Style
- 4 spaces, no tabs
- All public methods need Javadoc with @param, @return, @throws
- Single-statement if blocks MUST have braces
- No synchronized blocks in driver hot paths (writeAsync/read)
- Lombok is available (@Synchronized, @SuppressFBWarnings)

### File Structure
- Drivers: `drivers/<name>/src/main/java/io/sbk/driver/<Name>/<Name>.java`
- Config: `drivers/<name>/src/main/java/io/sbk/driver/<Name>/<Name>Config.java`
- Properties: `drivers/<name>/src/main/resources/<name>.properties`
- Package name matches directory name (case-sensitive)

### Common Gotchas
- Checkstyle import-control.xml needs new top-level packages whitelisted
- Pathing JAR can get stale after dependency changes - clean rebuild needed
- halodb driver is disabled due to GitHub Packages quota
- MinIO SDK is pinned to 8.5.17 (not 9.x) for backend compatibility
- Drivers must handle InterruptedIOException as clean shutdown

## When Adding a Driver

1. Copy from `drivers/sbktemplate/`
2. Rename packages and classes (SbkTemplate → YourDriver)
3. Add vendor SDK to build.gradle
4. Add to settings-drivers.gradle: `include 'drivers:yourdriver'`
5. Add to build-drivers.gradle: `api project(':drivers:yourdriver')`
6. Update checkstyle/import-control.xml if new packages
7. Implement Storage<T>, Writer<T>, Reader<T> interfaces
8. Add README.md with examples
9. Verify: `./gradlew :drivers:yourdriver:check`, `./gradlew check`, `./gradlew installDist`

## When Modifying Code

1. Run `./gradlew :module:check` for fast feedback
2. Run `./gradlew check` before committing
3. Test with real backend if it's a driver change
4. Update documentation (README.md, AGENTS.md, etc.)

## Verification Checklist

Before marking a task complete:
- [ ] ./gradlew check passes
- [ ] ./gradlew installDist succeeds
- [ ] No checkstyle violations
- [ ] Driver changes tested against real backend
- [ ] Documentation updated
- [ ] Both Gradle files updated for new drivers

